Note:
Runa Standard Library: Test Fixtures and Data Management System

Production-grade test data management framework designed to surpass
competitors like pytest fixtures, JUnit's @Before/@After, and TestNG's
data providers. Comprehensive fixture lifecycle and dependency management.

Key Features:
- Fixture creation with multiple scopes (function, class, module, session)
- Dependency injection with automatic resolution and circular detection
- Lazy loading and caching strategies for expensive fixtures
- Fixture parameterization for data-driven testing scenarios
- Cleanup and teardown management with guaranteed execution
- Fixture sharing across test modules and sessions
- Dynamic fixture generation based on test context
- Fixture serialization for distributed testing environments
- Resource management with automatic cleanup and leak prevention
- Fixture versioning and compatibility tracking
- Performance monitoring and optimization for fixture creation

Architecture:
Built on Runa's natural language primitives with dependency graph
resolution and lifecycle management. Provides both declarative fixture
definition and programmatic fixture factory APIs.
:End Note

Import "../../collections" as Collections
Import "string/format" as Format

Note: Core Fixture Types and Structures
Type called "Fixture":
    name as String
    factory_function as String
    scope as FixtureScope
    dependencies as List[String]
    parameters as Optional[List[Any]]
    cached_value as Optional[Any]
    cleanup_function as Optional[String]
    created_at as Optional[Float]
    access_count as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type FixtureScope is:
    | FunctionScope
    | ClassScope
    | ModuleScope
    | SessionScope
    | CustomScope with scope_name as String

Type called "FixtureRegistry":
    fixtures as Dictionary[String, Fixture]
    dependency_graph as Dictionary[String, List[String]]
    scope_managers as Dictionary[String, ScopeManager]
    active_instances as Dictionary[String, FixtureInstance]
    cleanup_stack as List[CleanupAction]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "FixtureInstance":
    fixture_name as String
    value as Any
    scope as FixtureScope
    created_at as Float
    dependencies as List[String]
    cleanup_scheduled as Boolean
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "ScopeManager":
    scope_name as String
    active_fixtures as List[String]
    cleanup_order as List[String]
    scope_started_at as Float
    scope_data as Dictionary[String, Any]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "CleanupAction":
    fixture_name as String
    cleanup_function as String
    priority as Integer
    execution_order as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "FixtureRequest":
    fixture_name as String
    requesting_context as String
    parameters as Optional[List[Any]]
    required_scope as FixtureScope
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "FixtureResult":
    success as Boolean
    value as Any
    creation_time as Float
    dependencies_resolved as List[String]
    error_message as String
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Fixture Registration and Management
Process called "create_fixture_registry" returns FixtureRegistry:
    Note: Create new fixture registry with default scope managers
    Let scope_managers be dictionary containing
    Set scope_managers at key "function" to create_scope_manager with name as "function"
    Set scope_managers at key "class" to create_scope_manager with name as "class"
    Set scope_managers at key "module" to create_scope_manager with name as "module"
    Set scope_managers at key "session" to create_scope_manager with name as "session"
    Return FixtureRegistry with:
    fixtures as dictionary containing
    dependency_graph as dictionary containing
    scope_managers as scope_managers
    active_instances as dictionary containing
    cleanup_stack as list containing
    metadata as dictionary containing "created_at" as get_current_timestamp

Process called "register_fixture" that takes registry as FixtureRegistry and fixture as Fixture returns FixtureRegistry:
    Note: Register fixture in registry with dependency validation
    Note: Validate fixture definition
    Let validation_result be validate_fixture_definition with fixture as fixture and registry as registry
    If not validation_result.valid:
    Set registry.metadata at key "last_error" to validation_result.error_message
    Return registry Note: Register the fixture
    Set registry.fixtures at key fixture.name to fixture Note: Update dependency graph
    Set registry.dependency_graph at key fixture.name to fixture.dependencies Note: Validate no circular dependencies
    Let circular_check be check_circular_dependencies with registry as registry
    If circular_check.has_cycles:
    Set registry.metadata at key "last_error" to "Circular dependency detected: " circular_check.cycle_description
    Remove fixture.name from registry.fixtures
    Remove fixture.name from registry.dependency_graph
    Return registry Set registry.metadata at key "fixture_count" to length of keys of registry.fixtures
    Set registry.metadata at key "last_registered" to fixture.name Return registry

Process called "fixture" that takes name as String and factory_function as String returns Fixture:
    Note: Create basic fixture with function scope
    Return Fixture with:
    name as name
    factory_function as factory_function
    scope as FunctionScope
    dependencies as list containing
    parameters as None
    cached_value as None
    cleanup_function as None
    created_at as None
    access_count as 0
    metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "fixture_with_scope" that takes name as String and factory_function as String and scope as FixtureScope returns Fixture:
    Note: Create fixture with specific scope
    Return Fixture with:
    name as name
    factory_function as factory_function
    scope as scope
    dependencies as list containing
    parameters as None
    cached_value as None
    cleanup_function as None
    created_at as None
